<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="10" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,317,709]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,583,608]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Remarks</emphasis>
. The present material is the first record of 
<taxonomicName box="[790,975,583,608]" class="Malacostraca" family="Alpheidae" genus="Alpheus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="thomasi">
<emphasis box="[790,975,583,608]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Alpheus thomasi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
for the Brazilian states of Ceará and Rio Grande do Norte. This colourful snapping shrimp, easily identifiable in the field by its diagnostic colour pattern (
<figureCitation box="[159,228,650,675]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1913,1935]" captionTargetBox="[151,1434,193,1890]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1436,193,1892]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 4. Alpheus thomasi Hendrix &amp; Gore, 1973: male (OUMNH. ZC. 2012 - 07 - 0032) and ovigerous female (RMNH D 54842) from Areia Branca, Rio Grande do Norte, Brazil; A, male in dorsal view; B, C, ovigerous female in dorsal (B) and lateral (C) views. Scale bars: 4 mm. Photographs by A. Anker." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/400301/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
Fig. 
<number box="[212,228,651,675]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" value="4.0">4</number>
</figureCitation>
, see also 
<bibRefCitation author="Hendrix" box="[336,587,650,675]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" refString="Hendrix, G. Y. &amp; Gore, R. H. (1973) Studies on decapod Crustacea from the Indian River region of Florida. I. Alpheus thomasi, new species, a new snapping shrimp from the subtropical east coast of Florida (Crustacea: Decapoda: Alpheidae). Proceedings of the Biological Society of Washington, 86, 413 - 422." type="journal article" year="1973">
Hendrix &amp; Gore 
<number box="[528,587,651,675]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" value="1973.0">1973</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Anker" box="[600,801,650,675]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" refString="Anker, A., Hurt, C. &amp; Knowlton, N. (2008) Revision of the Alpheus websteri Kingsley, 1880 species complex (Crustacea: Decapoda: Alpheidae), with revalidation of A. arenensis (Chace, 1937). Zootaxa, 1694, 51 - 68." type="journal article" year="2008">
Anker 
<emphasis box="[677,734,650,675]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">et al.</emphasis>
<number box="[741,801,651,675]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" value="2008.0">2008</number>
</bibRefCitation>
), appears to be relatively widespread in 
<collectingCountry box="[1255,1326,650,675]" name="Brazil" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, although localised and not very common.
</paragraph>
